"Lee Bor-Jih, Kltsukawa S., Nakagawa H., Asakura S., Fukuda K.","Direct conversion of methane to methanol using molten salts",1998,"Denki Kagaku","66","6",,"609","614",,,,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-33749433115&partnerID=40&md5=a385d918ad88cddb92e07a420bf6f6c6","Department of Materials Science and Chemical Engineering, Faculty of Engineering, Yokohama National University, 79-5 Tokiwadai, Hodogaya-ku, Yokohama, 240-8501, Japan","Lee Bor-Jih, Department of Materials Science and Chemical Engineering, Faculty of Engineering, Yokohama National University, 79-5 Tokiwadai, Hodogaya-ku, Yokohama, 240-8501, Japan; Kltsukawa, S., Department of Materials Science and Chemical Engineering, Faculty of Engineering, Yokohama National University, 79-5 Tokiwadai, Hodogaya-ku, Yokohama, 240-8501, Japan; Nakagawa, H., Department of Materials Science and Chemical Engineering, Faculty of Engineering, Yokohama National University, 79-5 Tokiwadai, Hodogaya-ku, Yokohama, 240-8501, Japan; Asakura, S., Department of Materials Science and Chemical Engineering, Faculty of Engineering, Yokohama National University, 79-5 Tokiwadai, Hodogaya-ku, Yokohama, 240-8501, Japan; Fukuda, K., Department of Materials Science and Chemical Engineering, Faculty of Engineering, Yokohama National University, 79-5 Tokiwadai, Hodogaya-ku, Yokohama, 240-8501, Japan","In recent years the world has become more concerned about the global warming problem. The major greenhouse gas-CO2 are produced mainly by the utilization and combustion of fossil fuels-natural gas, oil, and coal. Methanol is a cleaner fuel for the environment than oil and coal. It generates less CO2, NOX and SOX per unit of thermal energy, and is easier to handle than methane. The direct conversion of methane to methanol is a potential process for methanol production, although it has not been practiced on a commercial level to date. In the present study, nitrate melts were used as the promoters for the partial oxidation of methane to methanol. The results were compared to the data extracted from the literature using other melt salts. It has been found that the oxygen-containing product CH3OH formed in nitrate melts, whereas the products obtained in hydroxides, carbonates and chlorides were mainly C2H6 and C2H4. Summarizing the results obtained in our work and the previous studies, it was suggested that the reaction route proceeding to the oxidative coupling or the direct conversion to methanol can be controlled by a suitable choice of molten salts.","Global warming; Methane; Methanol; Molten salts",,,,,,,"Takakura, T., (1997) Journal of the Institute of Applied Energy, 20 (3), p. 58; Pinto, A., Rogerson, P.L., (1977) Chem. Eng., 4, p. 102; Edwarda, J.H., Foster, N.R., (1986) Fuel Science & Technology Int'l., 4, p. 365; Yarlagadda, P.S., Morton, L.A., Hunter, N.R., Cesser, H.D., (1988) Ind. Eng. Chem. Res., 27, p. 252; Durch, R., Squire, G.D., Tsang, S.C., (1989) J. Chem. Soc., Faraday Trans, L, 85, p. 3561; Rytz, D.W., Baiker, A., (1991) Ind. Eng. Chem. Res., 30, p. 2287; Foulds, G.A., Gray, B.F., Miller, S.A., Walker, O.S., (1993) Ind. Eng. Chem. Res., 3 (2), p. 780; Casey, P.S., Mcallister, T., Foger, K., (1994) Ind. Eng. Chem. Res., 33, p. 1120; Omata, K., Fukuoka, N., Fujimoto, K., (1994) Ind. Eng. Chem. Res., 33, p. 784; Han, L.B., Tsubota, S., Kobayashi, T., Haruta, M., J. Chem. Soc., Chem. Commun., 93, p. 1995; Chun, J.W., Anthony, R.G., (1993) Ind. Eng. Chem. Res., 32, p. 259; Walker, O.S., Lapszewicz, J.A., Foulds, G.A., (1994) Catal. Today, 21, p. 519; Moneuse, C., Cassir, M., Piolet, C., Devynck, J., (1990) Appl. Catal., 63, p. 67; Conway, S.J., Szanyi, J., Lunsford, J.H., (1989) Appl. Catal, 5 (6), p. 149; Moneuse, C., Cassir, M., Martin, G., Devynck, J., (1992) Appl. Catal., 85, p. 147; Ohtsuka, Y., Kuwabara, M., Tomita, A., (1989) Appl. Catal., 4 (7), p. 307; Zambonin, P.G., Jordan, J., (1967) 7. Amer. Chem. Soc., 8 (9), p. 6365; Zambonin, P.O., Jordan, J., (1969) J. Amer. Ch